  <section class="section"><div class="wrap narrow">
    <h2>Gaggenau — ultra-luxury BSH, modular wall-oven column</h2>
    <p>Gaggenau was founded in 1683 as a German iron works in the Black Forest region and entered luxury appliances mid-20th-century. The brand is now a Bosch Siemens Hausgeräte (BSH) subsidiary — BSH has been wholly-owned by Robert Bosch GmbH since 2015 when Bosch bought out Siemens' former 50% stake. Within the BSH portfolio, Gaggenau occupies the ultra-luxury global position above Thermador (luxury US) and Bosch (mainstream premium).</p>
    <p>Gaggenau's signature product concept is the <b>modular wall-oven column</b>: instead of a single wall oven, high-end Gaggenau-specified LA kitchens get a vertical column containing multiple specialized modules stacked together. A typical 400 Series column: BO (30" built-in oven, the core cooking module) + BS (combi-steam, for steam + convection cooking) + BM (speed oven, microwave + convection combo for rapid reheat) + BMP (warming drawer, for holding food at serving temp). Some columns add a BV vacuum-sealing drawer for sous-vide prep. Each module is a separate appliance with its own control platform, its own parts catalog, and its own service economics.</p>
    <p>US distribution runs through BSH Irvine CA — the same LA-local parts-chain advantage that benefits Thermador and Bosch service. Gaggenau specialty parts (400 Series control boards, combi-steam boiler hardware, warming-drawer-specific components) sometimes carry 3-7 day lead even through Irvine because of the low production volume; mainstream Gaggenau service parts run 2-4 day lead typical.</p>
  </div></section>

